<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg009' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 9</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >Third Philippic</title>, see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This is a speech that <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> gave at a meeting of the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term>, and then published later. He delivered this speech sometime in <date  when='-0341'>341 BCE</date>, shortly after the speech <title >On the <placeName  key='Chersonese'>Chersonese</placeName></title> (<bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg008' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 8</bibl>) (source for date: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 222</bibl>). In 341 <name  type='person'>Philip</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName> was waging war in <placeName  key='Thrace'>Thrace</placeName>, and so was the Athenian <term  sortKey='Military'>general</term> <name  type='person'>Diopithes</name>. At <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>, the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> was debating sending reinforcements to <name  type='person'>Diopithes</name>. <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, in this speech, urges <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to oppose <name  type='person'>Philip</name>, noting that the city must form alliances, since <name  type='person'>Philip</name> is too strong, and his territory too extensive, for <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to oppose him alone. The speech succeeded in urging the Athenians to action, and within a year <placeName  key='Byzantium'>Byzantium</placeName>, on the <placeName  key='Hellespont'>Hellespont</placeName>, <placeName  key='Euboea'>Euboea</placeName>, and several other Greek cities allied themselves with <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to oppose <name  type='person'>Philip</name>. (See also, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg004' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 4</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg006' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 6</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg010' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 10</bibl> — all speeches urging opposition to <name  type='person'>Philip</name>, and <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg008' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 8</bibl>, which deals with the same political developments in <placeName  key='Thrace'>Thrace</placeName>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
